[{"id":"VH970112","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"table_wrapper\">\n<table class=\"tgroup cols:3\">\n\t<colgroup>\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec align:center\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec align:center\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec align:center\" />\n\t</colgroup>\n\t<thead class=\"thead\">\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<th class=\"entry colname:col1\">Name</th>\n\t\t\t<th class=\"entry colname:col2\">Structure</th>\n\t\t\t<th class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"K sub a at 25 degrees Celsius \"><math alttext=\"K sub a at 25 degrees Celsius \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mstyle><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>(at</mtext><mtext> 25</mtext><mi>°</mi><mtext>C)</mtext></mrow></math></span></span></th>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</thead>\n\t<tbody class=\"tbody\">\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1\">Acid 1</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a Lewis structure. Two C atoms are connected by a single bond. The first C atom is connected to two Br atoms and one H atom by single bonds. The second C atom is connected to one O atom by a double bond and another O atom by a single bond. The single-bonded O atom is connected to an H atom by a single bond.\" height=\"94\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH970112.g03.png\" width=\"130\" /></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3.3 times 10 to the negative 2 power\"><math alttext=\"3.3 times 10 to the negative 2 power\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>3.3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col1\">Acid 2</td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a Lewis structure. Two C atoms are connected by a single bond. The first C atom is connected to three Br atoms by single bonds. The second C atom is connected to one O atom by a double bond and another O atom by a single bond. The single-bonded O atom is connected to an H atom by a single bond.\" height=\"94\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH970112.g04.png\" width=\"130\" /></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.9 times 10 to the negative 1 power\"><math alttext=\"1.9 times 10 to the negative 1 power\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1.9</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The table above provides information on two weak acids. Which of the following explains the difference in their acid strength?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH970112_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Acid 1 is a stronger acid because it has more acidic hydrogen atoms than acid 2.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Acid 1 is a stronger acid because it can make more hydrogen bonds than acid 2.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Acid 2 is a stronger acid because it is a larger, more polarizable molecule with stronger intermolecular forces than acid 1.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Acid 2 is a stronger acid because it has a more stable conjugate base than acid 1 due to the greater number of electronegative <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B r\"><math alttext=\"B r\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Br</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> atoms.</p>"],"answer":3}]